what the Indian writer and wildlife conservationist Valmik Thapar called “the greatest dislocation of habitat man has ever witnessed.”

In recent years the twilight of the ancient nomadic civilization in the Mongolian steppes— a slash-and-burn agriculture going back some 2,000 years— has been approached with various levels of government intervention. Since the beginning of the 20th century, the Mongolian government proclaimed religious immunities for divine deities and protected indigenous Right-of-Pasture (RoP) claims since 1921. For centuries the concept of land ownership was foreign in Mongolia. Peasants who lived in yak fur shacks in the countryside referred to the fence or outer edge of their commune as their home—instead of an actual house and yard. For generations yak-herding communities exchanged the herd’s milk and yaks for grain harvested from their neighbors. The Mongolian bandits look reminiscent of American cowboys and sometimes ranching outfits raise the same sort of animals.
